{
  "style": "APA",
  "texts": [
    "Remote sensing has been employed for increasing coverage of bloom observations, showing that algal blooms have been expanding and intensifying in many coastal areas due to environmental changes (Dai et al. 2023), even though the methods yield limited taxonomical information.",
    "Thus, methods that can quickly identify different species at high speed, such as imaging, can enhance our knowledge of the bloom-forming species dynamics for understanding plankton communities and to provide more accurate data for model validation information on a higher time scale is needed (Kraft et al. 2021).",
    "Studying and monitoring plankton is hindered by their microscopic size, fast turnover rates and close interaction with the multiscale hydrodynamics (Benfield et al. 2007).",
    "Recent advances in plankton imaging systems have led to their popularization and integration into monitoring programs, collectively accumulating information on plankton systems and simultaneously gathering massive amounts of image data (Benfield et al. 2007; Cowen and Guigand 2008; Lombard et al. 2019; Olson and Sosik 2007; Picheral et al. 2010).",
    "The major constraint to the use of these datasets lies in the expert annotation of plankton images, which is expensive, time-consuming, and error-prone."
  ],
